proof.p:
The Theorem is clearly true for the case of p=2 since any integer and its square have the same odd/even parity and their difference must be even.   We now assume that p is odd.   The theorem is clearly true for n=0.  This forms the basis for an induction poof for positive values of n.  Assume for some n \geq 0, that  n^p - n is divisible by p.  Now consider  (n+1)^p - (n+1).

  (n+1)^p - (n+1) \amp=   \left( n^p+\sum_{k=1}^{p-1} { \binom{p}{k} n^{p-k} } + 1\right) -n -1 
                  \amp= (n^p -n)  +\sum_{k=1}^{p-1} {\binom{p}{k} n^{p-k} }

solution.p:
Let p_n be the probability that after tossing the first n coins, an odd number of heads have appeared.  Clearly p_1 = \frac{1}{3}.  If n \gt 1,
 	\begin{split}
 		p_n &= \frac{1}{2n+1}  (1-p_{n-1}) + \frac{2n}{2n+1} p_{n-1}\\
 			& = \frac{2n-1}{2n+1}p_{n-1} + \frac{1}{2n+1}
 		\end{split}

If you use the formula to compute a few more terms of the sequence, the pattern p_n=\frac{n}{2n+1}  emerges and this can be proven by induction.

Let g(x) be an arbitrary polynomial of degree d+1 over the integers, then g(x) can be rewritten as g(x) = x\cdot h(x) + c, where h(x) has degree d and c is an integer. Then
\begin{split} \sum_{k=0}^{n} (-1)^k\binom{n}{k}g(k) &= \sum_{k=0}^{n} (-1)^k\binom{n}{k}\left[kh(k) + c\right]\\ & = \sum_{k=0}^{n} (-1)^k\binom{n}{k}k \cot h(k) + \sum_{k=0}^{n} (-1)^k\binom{n}{k}c. \end{split}
The second term is 0 which is proven by , while
\begin{split} \sum_{k=0}^{n} (-1)^k\binom{n}{k}k\cdot h(k) &= (-1)^0\binom{n}{0}0\cdot h(0) + \sum_{k=1}^{n} (-1)^k\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}k\cdot h(k)\\ & = 0 + \sum_{k=1}^{n} (-1)^k\frac{n!}{(k-1)!(n-k)!}h(k)\\ & = -n\sum_{k=1}^{n} (-1)^{k-1}\frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)!(n-k)!}h(k) \\ &= -n\sum_{k=1}^{n} (-1)^{k-1}\binom{n-1}{k-1}h(k)\\ & = -n\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (-1)^k\binom{n-1}{k}h(k+1) \end{split}

statement.p:
Given a sequence of integers x_1, x_2, \dots x_n whose sum is 1, prove that exactly one of the cyclic shifts
x_1,x_2,\dots ,x_n x_2,\dots,x_n,x_1 \vdots x_n,x_1,\dots,x_{n-1}
has all of its partial sums positive. (By a partial sum we mean the sum of the first k terms, k \leq n.
